<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-09-08T07:24:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-09-08T07:24:00-05:00" n="784" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d784">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">760c.60m/11: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Commissioner at Riga</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Young</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Riga</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-09-08T14:00:00+01:36"><hi rend="italic">September
                                            8, 1920—2 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received September
                                    5—3:12 a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                            <p>134. British Commissioner here endeavoring to arrange for
                                Polish-Lithuanian conference with a view to examination and
                                settlement <pb facs="0760" n="660" xml:id="pg_660"/> all disputes
                                and controversies and for agreement to refer to League of Nations
                                for determination all disputes not settled at the proposed
                                conference.</p>
                            <p>Learn through confidential sources my name under consideration as
                                chairman proposed conference. What would be Department’s attitude?
                                Personally I do not believe it would be wise in view of our
                                non-recognition Lithuania.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Young</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>